Major-General '''Warren Melville Anderson''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] (31 August 1894<U+2014>10 February 1973) was an [[general officer]] in the [[Australian Army]], who served in both World Wars.

==Biography==
The eldest son of Marsham Ambrose Anderson, he was educated at the [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]], and was commissioned as a [[lieutenant]] on 3 November 1914 in B Squadron, 6th [[Australian Light Horse|Light Horse]] Regiment.<ref name="unithistories">{{cite web |url= http://www.unithistories.com/officers/AustrArmy_officers.html |title=Australian Army Officers 1939-1945 | coauthors= Hans Houterman & Jeroen Koppes |work=World War II Unit Histories & Officers |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref>

===World War I===
Anderson and his squadron sailed from [[Sydney]] on board [[SS Suevic|HMAT (A29) ''Suevic'']] on 21 December 1914, <ref>{{cite web |url= http://alh-research.tripod.com/Light_Horse/index.blog/1982048/6th-australian-light-horse-regiment-embarkation-roll-b-squadron/ |title=6th Australian Light Horse Regiment Embarkation Roll, "B" Squadron |work=Australian Light Horse Studies Centre |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> and arrived in Egypt on 1 February 1915. After serving as infantry in the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] between May and December 1915, the Light Horsemen were stationed in Egypt as part of the [[ANZAC Mounted Division]]. They played an important role in the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign|advance into Palestine]], taking part in several major actions up until the [[Armistice of Mudros|Armistice of 30 October 1918]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://alh-research.tripod.com/Light_Horse/index.blog/1861979/6th-australian-light-horse-regiment-aif-history/ |title=6th Australian Light Horse Regiment, AIF |work=Australian Light Horse Studies Centre |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> In the course of the war Anderson was advanced to the acting-rank of captain and then major,<ref name="unithistories"/> serving as [[Brigade Major]] in the [[3rd Light Horse Brigade]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/AWM28/2/128/0017.pdf |title=Honours and Awards - Warren Melville Anderson |work=Australian War Memorial |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> part of the [[Australian Mounted Division]]. Anderson received two [[Mentioned in Despatches|Mentions in Despatches]] (in January 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30474 |date=14 January 1918 |startpage=804 |supp=yes |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> and January 1919<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31138 |date=22 January 1919 |startpage=1164 |supp= |accessdate=17 October 2011 }}</ref>), and was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] in the 1919 New Years Honours List.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31093 |date=31 December 1918 |startpage=55 |supp=yes |accessdate=17 October 2011 }}</ref>

===Inter-war years===
From February 1920 Anderson served as a [[Staff (military)|General Staff Officer]], 3rd grade (GSO3) in the [[6th Military District (Australia)|6th Military District]], receiving promotion to [[Captain (OF-2)|captain]] on 30 September, and subsequently serving as a staff officer in the 1st Cavalry Division from May 1921, and then in the 2nd Division from August 1922. Between December 1922 and December 1924 he served as the Brigade Major of the [[1st Brigade (Australia)|1st Infantry Brigade]], before attending the [[Command and Staff College|Staff College, Quetta]] until February 1927. He then served in the [[Inspector General]]'s Branch until May 1928, then as a General Staff Officer in charge of Training, based at Army Headquarters until January 1932. He served as Brigade Major in the 3rd Cavalry Brigade between February and August 1932, finally receiving promotion to the rank of [[major]] on 1 September 1932. He then served as a temporary staff officer in the 2nd Cavalry Division, before becoming Brigade Major in the 5th and then the [[6th Cavalry Brigade (Australia)|6th Cavalry Brigades]]. In November 1936 Anderson was appointed to the staff of the 1st Cavalry Division, and was promoted to [[lieutenant colonel]] on 3 July 1938.<ref name="unithistories"/>

===World War II===
Between March 1939 and January 1940 Anderson served [[Exchange officer|on exchange]] in the [[Meerut district]] of India, returning to Australia in 8 January 1940 to join the staff of the [[4th Division (Australia)|4th Division]]. In April 1940 he was appointed Director of Staff Duties, with the rank of temporary colonel. On 1 July 1941 he was promoted to [[colonel]] and transferred to the [[Royal Australian Armoured Corps|Australian Armoured Corps]], part of the [[Second Australian Imperial Force]], serving as Assistant Adjutant and Quartermaster-General of the [[1st Armoured Division (Australia)|1st Armoured Division]] until January 1942.<ref name="unithistories"/> After a brief term as Director of Military Training in early 1942,<ref name="unithistories"/> he returned to staff duties with the rank of [[brigadier]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ordersofbattle.com/PersonData.aspx?PerX=28337&Tab=App&Titl=WM%20Anderson |title=Warren Melville Anderson |work=Orders of Battle Second World War Military Unit Database |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> serving with [[III Corps (Australia)|III Corps]] until June 1943, [[Second Army (Australia)|Second Army]] until August 1943, then at the Advanced Land HQ at [[St Lucia, Queensland]], until January 1944.<ref name="unithistories"/> Anderson was on the staff of the [[Northern Territory Force]] until August 1944, with two brief periods as Acting-[[General Officer Commanding|GOC]] in February/March and August.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.generals.dk/general/Anderson/Warren_Melville/Australia.html |title=Biography of Major-General Warren Melville Anderson |first=Steen |last=Ammentorp  |work=The Generals of WWII |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> From September 1944 until the end of the war in August 1945 he was attached as Brigadier in charge of Administration to the [[Eighth United States Army]].<ref name="unithistories"/>

===Post-war===
Anderson was made a Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (Military Division) in November 1946,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37898 |date=4 March 1947 |startpage=1085 |supp=yes |accessdate=17 October 2011 }}</ref> and from 1947 he served as [[Adjutant general|Adjutant-General]] of the [[Australian Military Forces]] and Second Member of the Military Board until he retired with the rank of [[major general]] in 1951.<ref name="unithistories"/>

===Personal life===
Anderson married Violet Clark in 1928.<ref name="unithistories"/> He died at his home in [[Darling Point, New South Wales]] in 10 February 1973.

